    llmWikiLabel_learnings: "What I learned",
    llmWikiProblem_p1: "Every university course dumps the same amount of material on you: lectures, practice guides, past exams, community summaries. By the end of a semester, you're sitting on 50+ PDFs with no unified way to navigate them, search across them, or understand how they relate to each other.",
    llmWikiProblem_p2: "The naive fix — dumping everything into a chat window — doesn't scale. You burn tokens, lose structure, and the model forgets what it read three PDFs ago. There had to be a better way.",
    llmWikiProblem_p3: "What I actually needed was a system that understood how I study: exams are the north star, practice guides are the training ground, and lectures are the reference. None of the off-the-shelf tools (Notion, Anki, even manual Obsidian) understood that hierarchy.",
    llmWikiInsight_p1: "Inspired by Andrej Karpathy's \"LLM Wiki\" idea, I landed on a simple but powerful reframe: instead of using the LLM as an oracle, use it as a maintainer. Claude Code does the boring work — parsing PDFs, creating structured pages, cross-referencing exercises, updating the log. I do the learning.",
    llmWikiInsight_p2: "The result: a parse-once, query-many architecture. Every PDF is processed exactly one time and stored as structured Markdown in an Obsidian vault. From that point on, all queries work against clean, well-organized text — never against raw PDFs again.",
    llmWikiInsight_p3: "And the most important design decision: ingest exams first. Everything else (lectures, guides) is cross-referenced against them. That way, when you study a topic, you already know which exercises appeared in which exams and how often.",
    llmWikiHowItWorks_p1: "Each university subject gets its own isolated folder with a consistent structure: raw PDFs go in, Markdown wiki pages come out. The system supports 7 distinct page types — theory extractions, practice sessions, guide exercises, analyzed exams, handwritten transcriptions, exercise-type pattern pages, and synthesis notes.",
    llmWikiHowItWorks_p2a: "PDF extraction uses a dual strategy: ",
    llmWikiHowItWorks_p2b: " handles LaTeX-compiled lecture slides fast and reliably. When it returns less than 500 characters on a multi-page document — a reliable signal for scanned or handwritten content — it falls back to Claude's vision capabilities. One command handles both cases transparently.",
    llmWikiHowItWorks_p3: "The whole lifecycle is driven by 11 slash commands defined as Markdown files in .claude/commands/. They're version-controlled, readable, and easy to customize. /ingestar parses a PDF, /resolver works through pending exercises, /simular generates exam-style practice problems, and /chuleta assembles a consolidated cheat sheet on any topic.",
    llmWikiArch_1_title: "Dual parse pipeline",
    llmWikiArch_1_desc: "pdftotext for LaTeX slides (fast, exact). Claude vision as automatic fallback for scanned exams and handwritten content — triggered by a <500 char heuristic.",
    llmWikiArch_2_title: "7-type page taxonomy",
    llmWikiArch_2_desc: "Every page has a type, YAML frontmatter, and Obsidian cross-links. Content is structured for LLM retrieval first, human navigation second.",
    llmWikiArch_3_title: "11 slash commands",
    llmWikiArch_3_desc: "Full study lifecycle in code: ingest, resolve, lint, simulate, cheat-sheet. Each command is a Markdown file — readable, version-controlled, customizable.",
    llmWikiArch_4_title: "Exam-first design",
    llmWikiArch_4_desc: "Past exams are ingested before anything else. Every exercise in lectures and guides is then flagged with its exam appearances, so patterns emerge naturally.",
    llmWikiOutcome_1: "51 PDFs processed — 36+ structured wiki pages generated across 10 algorithm topics.",
    llmWikiOutcome_2: "13 exercise-type pattern pages capturing recurring exam structures (Master Theorem, exchange-argument proofs, flow modeling, etc.).",
    llmWikiOutcome_3: "6 past exams fully analyzed with solutions, explanations, and cross-references.",
    llmWikiOutcome_4: "11 slash commands covering the full study lifecycle, from raw PDF to exam simulation.",
    llmWikiOutcome_5: "Pilot subject (Algorithms & Data Structures III) at 88% completion.",
    llmWikiOutcome_6: "Architecture is fully reusable — adding a new subject is one new folder.",
    llmWikiLearnings_p1: "The biggest shift was learning to design for LLM retrieval, not human browsing. A well-structured wiki page isn't the same as a readable article. Focused, narrow pages with explicit metadata outperform monolithic documents — even when the monolith \"reads\" better.",
    llmWikiLearnings_p2: "I also learned the value of separating phases of work. Ingestion (parse, structure, link) and resolution (think, solve, synthesize) are cognitively different tasks. Mixing them in one session leads to shallow output on both. The two-phase guide workflow — ingest first, solve separately — produced dramatically better results.",
    llmWikiLearnings_p3: "Building slash commands as Markdown files taught me something about automation philosophy: the best automations are the ones you can read, edit, and understand without running them first. Treating commands as documentation meant they improved over time instead of becoming black boxes.",
