    // Enterprise RAG System
    ragSystemHero_badge: "Completed",
    ragSystemHero_tagline: "A full-stack RAG assistant for enterprise onboarding — ingests Oracle ERP SOPs, answers questions in Spanish, and cites its sources.",
    ragSystemTldr_heading: "TL;DR",
    ragSystemTldr_b1: "8-node LangGraph pipeline: image grounding → query expansion → hybrid retrieval → reranking → generation.",
    ragSystemTldr_b2: "Hybrid search (vector + keyword + RRF) with bge-reranker achieves MRR@5 = 0.861 on a 12-query golden evaluation set.",
    ragSystemTldr_b3: "Multimodal: users attach error screenshots; Gemini Flash grounds them into Spanish descriptions before retrieval.",
    ragSystemLabel_problem: "The Problem",
    ragSystemLabel_insight: "The Insight",
    ragSystemLabel_howItWorks: "How It Works",
    ragSystemLabel_architecture: "Architecture Highlights",
    ragSystemLabel_techStack: "Tech Stack",
    ragSystemLabel_outcomes: "Outcomes & Status",
    ragSystemLabel_learnings: "What I Learned",
    ragSystemProblem_p1: "New hires at an Oracle ERP consulting firm face a brutal onboarding: dozens of SOP documents, hundreds of pages, screenshots of UI flows that need to be interpreted step by step. There's no index, no search, and no way to ask a question — just a pile of PDFs and a senior engineer who's already busy.",
    ragSystemProblem_p2: "The workaround was to call the senior engineer. Every time. Which meant that institutional knowledge lived in one person's head, onboarding took weeks instead of days, and the same questions got answered over and over.",
    ragSystemProblem_p3: "I was doing technical support at this company. I had a front-row seat to the problem. And I thought: this is exactly what RAG was made for.",
    ragSystemInsight_p1: "The insight wasn't that RAG exists — it was understanding what enterprise RAG actually needs to work in this context. Off-the-shelf embedding + generate is not enough when your documents are SOP PDFs with interface screenshots, your users ask in Spanish, and you need the system to cite its sources.",
    ragSystemInsight_p2: "You need hybrid retrieval (vector and keyword) fused with RRF, a cross-encoder reranker to re-score on semantic relevance, and a multimodal pipeline to handle UI screenshots. You also need intent routing — some questions are general, some need retrieval, some need a live web search.",
    ragSystemInsight_p3: "Once I understood that, the architecture became clear: not one model doing everything, but a graph of specialized nodes, each doing one job well.",
    ragSystemHowItWorks_p1: "Documents are uploaded through an admin console and sent to a FastAPI ingestion pipeline. Docling parses the PDF structure — preserving section hierarchy and extracting embedded images. Each image gets described by Gemini Flash vision and stored as a text chunk alongside the surrounding prose.",
    ragSystemHowItWorks_p2a: "Text is split into hierarchical chunks using section headings as natural boundaries — not arbitrary token counts. Each chunk carries metadata: document ID, section title, page number, and a SHA-256 hash for idempotent deduplication — then embedded with ",
    ragSystemHowItWorks_p2b: " and stored in Supabase pgvector alongside rich JSONB metadata.",
    ragSystemHowItWorks_p3: "At query time, an 8-node LangGraph graph runs: intent routing (RAG vs. general vs. web search) → optional image grounding → query expansion (3 variants) → parallel hybrid retrieval (vector + Spanish FTS keyword, RRF-fused) → bge-reranker-v2-m3 reranking → Gemini Flash generation in Spanish with inline citations.",
    ragSystemArch_1_title: "Hybrid Retrieval + RRF",
    ragSystemArch_1_desc: "Parallel vector search (pgvector) and Spanish full-text keyword search, fused with Reciprocal Rank Fusion. Top-20 candidates are passed to a bge-reranker for semantic re-scoring.",
    ragSystemArch_2_title: "LangGraph Orchestration",
    ragSystemArch_2_desc: "8-node graph with conditional edges: intent routing branches to RAG, general response, or Tavily web search. All paths converge at the generation node.",
    ragSystemArch_3_title: "Multimodal Ingestion",
    ragSystemArch_3_desc: "Docling extracts PDF structure and embedded images. Each image is described by Gemini Flash vision and stored as a searchable text chunk with its spatial metadata.",
    ragSystemArch_4_title: "Supabase as the Data Layer",
    ragSystemArch_4_desc: "Single platform for auth (JWT + RLS), vector store (pgvector), file storage, realtime ingestion progress, and PostgreSQL — no separate services to manage.",
    ragSystemOutcome_1: "End-to-end RAG pipeline fully implemented: ingestion, embedding, retrieval, reranking, and generation.",
    ragSystemOutcome_2: "Hybrid retrieval + bge-reranker achieves MRR@5 = 0.861 and Recall@10 = 0.872 on a 12-query golden evaluation set.",
    ragSystemOutcome_3: "Multimodal support: users attach screenshots; the system grounds them and incorporates them into retrieval.",
    ragSystemOutcome_4: "Intent routing sends general questions to direct LLM response and out-of-domain questions to Tavily web search.",
    ragSystemOutcome_5: "LangSmith tracing and evaluation wired for every run — full observability on retrieval quality and generation.",
    ragSystemOutcome_6: "Delivered as a PoC to company leadership, demonstrating real-world viability for a production rollout.",
    ragSystemLearnings_p1: "This project forced me to actually understand RAG — not just the concept, but every layer of it. Chunking strategy matters enormously: fixed-size splits lose section context; hierarchical chunking around real document structure produces dramatically better retrievals. The difference isn't theoretical — I watched MRR jump when I switched.",
    ragSystemLearnings_p2: "LangGraph taught me how to think about LLM architectures as graphs, not scripts. Each node has one job: expand the query, embed it, retrieve, rerank, generate. The conditional edge system made it natural to add intent routing and web search without touching the core RAG path — the graph absorbed complexity instead of spreading it.",
    ragSystemLearnings_p3: "Reranking surprised me. I assumed good retrieval was enough. It wasn't. The cross-encoder reranker added +0.147 lift over the already-tuned hybrid retrieval — meaning the top-5 results after reranking were meaningfully better than before. Retrieval quality and ranking quality are genuinely different problems.",
    ragSystemLearnings_p4: "The project ended as a proof of concept — something I built to make the internal case for a production version. That outcome shaped how I think about engineering projects: building a compelling PoC that demonstrates real value is its own skill, separate from production engineering. And sometimes it's the most important step.",
    ragSystemCta_title: "View the source",
    ragSystemCta_desc: "Full repo — FastAPI backend, Next.js frontend, LangGraph pipeline, and Docling ingestion on GitHub.",
    ragSystemCta_btn: "GitHub ↗",
    ragSystemRelated_heading: "Related projects",
